&gt;&gt;He accounts for embodied carbon under "lifecycle emissions."
&gt;
&gt;No. He uses someone else's estimates of embodied carbon as part of an LCA. Embodied carbon is one input into that. He doesn't state where the panels come from (this can double the embodied carbon in a panel), what the assumptions are in terms of panel longevity, nor address variation in output based on siting. What he gives is a derived value from someone else's paper, but the doesn't give the assumptions themselves. 
&gt;

So he can't build on someone else's research? 

&gt;&gt;He uses non-US nuclear plants in his analysis of construction delay timelines.
&gt;
&gt;Yes, he does. I need to correct that. He cherry picks the worst examples around the world. 

Don't have data on this readily available, so I suppose you may be correct. Do you have a good example of a nuclear plant going up quickly?

&gt;
&gt;&gt;And intermittency doesn't need to be addressed when the metric is cost per killowatt-hour, since intermittency is accounted for in the cost metric.
&gt;
&gt;Bullshit. Intermittency most certainly isn't address in the cost metric. The only occurrences of the word only occur in the footnotes, and all of them in titles of papers he himself has written.

His cost metric is dollar per killowatt-hour. How do you capture intermittency in that unit?

You can't, because it is implicitly captured. The solar panels don't produce energy when it is dark, but that doesn't matter because this paper is concerned with the total energy output by the end of life. Whether it's constantly producing electricity like nuclear or is idle at night like solar _is irrelevant_ when your metric is total energy output.
